# Secrets Management (shh)

This project uses [shh](https://github.com/stefanpenner/shh) for encrypted secrets.
Secrets are stored in `.env.enc` (age-encrypted TOML, safe to commit).

## Quick reference

- `shh login` — Set up your key (first time)
- `shh set KEY value` — Add/update a secret (`shh set KEY -` to read from stdin)
- `shh rm KEY` — Remove a secret
- `shh list` — Show secret names (no values)
- `shh edit` — Edit all secrets in $EDITOR
- `shh run -- <cmd>` — Run a command with secrets injected
- `shh shell` — Interactive shell with secrets loaded
- `shh env` — Print export statements
- `shh users add <github-username>` — Grant access to a teammate
- `shh users remove <user>` — Revoke access (rotates data key)
- `shh doctor` — Health check

## Rules

- NEVER commit plaintext `.env` files
- NEVER log, print, or echo secret values
- Use `shh set KEY -` (stdin) instead of `shh set KEY value` to avoid exposing values in shell history / `ps`
- When adding env vars to code, use `shh set` — do not edit `.env.enc` by hand
- After `shh users remove`, the data key is rotated — all secrets are re-encrypted
- CI uses `SHH_AGE_KEY` env var (deploy key) — never print or log it

## Multiple environments

- Default: `.env.enc`
- `shh -e staging set KEY value` uses `staging.env.enc`
- `shh -e production set KEY value` uses `production.env.enc`
